        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>The architecture consists of a complete CI/CD workflow from code commit to production deployment:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Developer</strong> – Writes code locally and tests using SAM CLI with Docker.</li>
                <li><strong>GitHub Repository</strong> – Stores source code, SAM templates, and pipeline configuration.</li>
                <li><strong>GitHub Actions</strong> – Triggered on push to main branch; runs build, test, and deploy jobs.</li>
                <li><strong>AWS SAM</strong> – Packages and deploys serverless applications using CloudFormation.</li>
                <li><strong>S3 Artifact Buckets</strong> – Stores deployment artifacts for Dev and Prod stages.</li>
                <li><strong>CloudFormation Stacks</strong> – Creates and manages Lambda, API Gateway, and IAM resources.</li>
                <li><strong>Lambda Function</strong> – Runs the serverless application code (Python).</li>
                <li><strong>API Gateway</strong> – Exposes the Lambda function as a REST API endpoint.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Pipeline Stages -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Pipeline Stages</h3>
            <p>The CI/CD pipeline follows a two-stage deployment model:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Stage 1: Dev Environment</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Triggered automatically on every push to main branch.</li>
                        <li>Builds and packages the SAM application.</li>
                        <li>Deploys to the Dev CloudFormation stack (sam-app-dev).</li>
                        <li>Runs integration tests against the Dev environment.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Stage 2: Prod Environment</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Deploys to Production after successful Dev deployment.</li>
                        <li>Uses separate IAM roles and S3 buckets for isolation.</li>
                        <li>Creates the Prod CloudFormation stack (sam-app-prod).</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Used <strong>sam init</strong> to scaffold a serverless application with best practices.</li>
                <li>Tested Lambda functions locally using <strong>sam local invoke</strong> with Docker.</li>
                <li>Bootstrapped multi-stage pipeline resources using <strong>sam pipeline init --bootstrap</strong>.</li>
                <li>Configured GitHub Actions workflow for automated CI/CD deployments.</li>
                <li>Managed AWS credentials securely using GitHub Secrets.</li>
                <li>Understood how SAM abstracts CloudFormation for serverless deployments.</li>
                <li>Learned the importance of separate environments (Dev/Prod) for safe deployments.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates a production-ready CI/CD workflow for serverless applications:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Use <strong>separate AWS accounts or profiles</strong> for Dev and Prod environments.</li>
                <li>Store AWS credentials in <strong>GitHub Secrets</strong>, never in code.</li>
                <li>Use <strong>IAM roles with least privilege</strong> for pipeline execution and CloudFormation.</li>
                <li>Enable <strong>CloudWatch Logs</strong> for Lambda function monitoring.</li>
                <li>Consider adding <strong>manual approval gates</strong> before production deployments.</li>
                <li>Clean up CloudFormation stacks when no longer needed to avoid costs.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

